[{"issueId":"cf92bfc8-e02a-4e91-aaaf-a7bef79b0340","aiExplanation":"This text has a color contrast ratio of only 3.5:1, but WCAG AA requires at least 4.5:1 for normal text. Users with low vision, color blindness, or age-related vision changes will struggle to read this content. Even users with normal vision may have difficulty in bright lighting conditions or on lower-quality displays. This issue can make critical information inaccessible and creates a frustrating reading experience.","aiFixSuggestion":"Increase the contrast ratio to at least 4.5:1 by either darkening the text color or lightening the background. Use a contrast checker tool to verify your changes.

Option 1 - Darken the text:
Before:
<p class="low-contrast">Sample text with low contrast</p>
/* CSS: color: #767676; background: #ffffff; */

After:
<p class="low-contrast">Sample text with low contrast</p>
/* CSS: color: #595959; background: #ffffff; */ /* 7:1 ratio */

Option 2 - Lighten the background:
/* CSS: color: #767676; background: #f5f5f5; won't help much */
/* Instead, keep white background and darken text */

Recommended: Use colors like #595959 on white for body text, or #2B47A3 (your site's primary color appears to have good contrast).","aiPriority":8},{"issueId":"eec7c0ae-3667-4873-bb68-2ed3c6d2e972","aiExplanation":"This image has no alt attribute, which means screen reader users cannot understand what it represents. When a screen reader encounters this image, it will either skip it entirely, announce 'image', or read the unhelpful filename 'logo.png'. If this is a meaningful image (like a company logo), blind users miss important visual information. If it's decorative, it still creates noise in the screen reader experience without an empty alt attribute to signal it should be skipped.","aiFixSuggestion":"Add an alt attribute with descriptive text that conveys the image's purpose and content. The appropriate alt text depends on the image's function:

If it's a logo that identifies the site:
Before:
<img src="logo.png">

After:
<img src="logo.png" alt="COC Layouts logo">

If the logo is also a link to the home page, make that clear:
<img src="logo.png" alt="COC Layouts - Home">

If it's purely decorative with no informational value:
<img src="logo.png" alt="">

Never omit the alt attribute entirely - always include it, even if empty for decorative images.","aiPriority":7},{"issueId":"9713c6e0-433f-4e34-8e19-f01deeb0d764","aiExplanation":"This link contains only an icon with no text, making it completely meaningless to screen reader users. When a screen reader encounters this link, it will announce only 'link' with no indication of where the link goes or what action it performs. Users navigating by keyboard who tab to this link will have no idea what it does. This creates a frustrating guessing game and may cause users to skip important functionality.","aiFixSuggestion":"Add accessible text to the link so screen reader users understand its purpose. There are several approaches:

Option 1 - Add visually hidden text (recommended for icon-only design):
Before:
<a href="/page"><i class="icon"></i></a>

After:
<a href="/page">
  <i class="icon" aria-hidden="true"></i>
  <span class="sr-only">View page</span>
</a>

/* CSS for sr-only class: */
.sr-only {
  position: absolute;
  width: 1px;
  height: 1px;
  padding: 0;
  margin: -1px;
  overflow: hidden;
  clip: rect(0, 0, 0, 0);
  border: 0;
}

Option 2 - Use aria-label:
<a href="/page" aria-label="View page"><i class="icon"></i></a>

Option 3 - Add visible text alongside the icon:
<a href="/page"><i class="icon"></i> View page</a>

Also add aria-hidden="true" to the icon to prevent screen readers from attempting to announce it.","aiPriority":6}]
